2026-03-31 | Construct Lexicographically Smallest Valid Word

Question:
•	You are given:
		str1 → tells constraints ('T' or 'F')  
		str2 → pattern string  

•	You must construct a string `word` of length n + m - 1  

•	Rules:
	- If str1[i] == 'T':
			word[i … i+m-1] must equal str2  
	- If str1[i] == 'F':
			word[i … i+m-1] must NOT equal str2  

•	Goal:
		find the **lexicographically smallest valid word**  

	Approach
1.	Initialize result string:
		word = '?' of length (n + m - 1)

2.	Apply all 'T' constraints:
		for each i where str1[i] == 'T':
			for j in [0, m-1]:
				if conflict → return ""
				else assign word[i+j] = str2[j]

3.	Fill remaining '?' with smallest char 'a'

4.	Handle 'F' constraints:
		for each i where str1[i] == 'F':
			check if substring == str2  
			if yes:
				try to break match by modifying one position  
				change smallest possible character  
				(if impossible → return "")

5.	Return final word

	Time Complexity
	O(n × m)

	Space Complexity
	O(n + m)

	Solution

class Solution {
public:
    string generateString(string str1, string str2) {

        int n = str1.size();
        int m = str2.size();

        string word(n + m - 1, '?');

        // Step 1: Apply 'T' constraints
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            if(str1[i] == 'T'){
                for(int j = 0; j < m; j++){
                    if(word[i+j] != '?' && word[i+j] != str2[j])
                        return "";
                    word[i+j] = str2[j];
                }
            }
        }

        // Step 2: Fill remaining with 'a'
        for(char &c : word){
            if(c == '?') c = 'a';
        }

        // Step 3: Fix 'F' constraints
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++){
            if(str1[i] == 'F'){

                bool match = true;
                for(int j = 0; j < m; j++){
                    if(word[i+j] != str2[j]){
                        match = false;
                        break;
                    }
                }

                if(match){
                    bool changed = false;

                    for(int j = 0; j < m; j++){
                        char original = word[i+j];

                        for(char c = 'a'; c <= 'z'; c++){
                            if(c == str2[j]) continue;

                            word[i+j] = c;

                            bool stillMatch = true;
                            for(int k = 0; k < m; k++){
                                if(word[i+k] != str2[k]){
                                    stillMatch = false;
                                    break;
                                }
                            }

                            if(!stillMatch){
                                changed = true;
                                break;
                            }
                        }

                        if(changed) break;
                        word[i+j] = original;
                    }

                    if(!changed) return "";
                }
            }
        }

        return word;
    }
};

	Key Insight
•	First strictly satisfy all **'T' constraints**  
•	Then ensure **'F' constraints** by breaking matches minimally  
•	Greedy replacement ensures **lexicographically smallest result**  

This is a **constraint satisfaction + greedy correction** problem.
